=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 3217<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/4/03 7:44:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=274.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Columbia</span><hr size=1> Here's what I scribbled down quickly and wrote back.<br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
Perhaps one of the best arguments for allowing nuclear power to increase our foothold in space is provided by Daniel Durda, a senior research scientist at the Southwest Research Institute in Boulder, Colorado.<br>
<br>
&quot;The worst scenario I can think of is a multi-kilometer-diameter, long-period comet discovered several months out on an impact trajectory as it is entering the inner solar system,&quot; he said. &quot;There is absolutely nothing we could do about it at this point in time. Nothing.&quot; <br>
<br>
Karl Grossman once contacted me by email and asked how I and the organization could believe in the use of nuclear power on space devices and why we thought it was safe and necessary, etc. My reply was that we don't believe nuclear power is completely safe. What we believe is that the risk is acceptable. Nuclear power would greatly enhance the manned exploration of our solar system. This is what we would like to see happen. That's our mission statement. All technology is a two edged sword and must pass a trial of fire. Technological progress has always been a target for fearmongers. I can imagine imagine a bunch of cavemen sitting around a damp cave tens of thousands of years ago arguing the pros and cons of trying to tame fire.<br>
&quot;Making fire is taboo. You will kill us all.&quot;<br>
&quot;We can warm our homes in winter and cook our food.&quot;<br>
The Pro-Nuclear Space Movement or NS is simply a grassroots organisation open for anyone interested in either space travel or nuclear power. A place to come and meet others, share views and discuss nuclear and/or space related issues. We've been around for quite a number of years, but only recently become more active thanks to the new nuclear initiative. <br>
Personally, I believe that the big fireworks used by Nasa just don't measure up against the challenge of space. Spaceflight was never for the timid and nuclear power is the only serious option for serious spaceflight.<br>
<br>
 Opposition movements to nuclear power in space are fond of fearmongering campaigns. Often associated with conspiracy theorists and anti-technologists, their arguments fall into two shallow categories. Gutter science which is easily disproved or simply accusing others of lying.<br>
<br>
Here are some examples from the Global Network Against Weapons And Nuclear Power In Space.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;In 1997 NASA launched the Cassini space probe carrying 72 pounds of plutonium that fortunately did not experience failure. If it had, hundreds of thousands of people around the world could have been contaminated.&quot;<br>
<br>
Hundreds of thousands contaminated they say. What is the risk mitigation source for that statement? The actual available evidence indicates that a worstcase scenario would be unlikely to cause a single fatality. <br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;Beyond accidents impacting the planet, the space nuclear production process at the DoE labs will lead to significant numbers of workers and communities being contaminated.&quot; <br>
<br>
Beer is 13 times more radioactive than the cooling water discharged from a nuclear power plant. We are contaminated every time we walk out into the sun. By not giving contamination levels it is an empty statement. The number one source of man made radiation released into the environment is from X-ray diagnostics believe it or not. Far outstripping fallout, Chernobyl, office equipment and all others combined. Safety regulations administering the operation of nuclear plants are already excessively stringent. If the White House was a nuclear power plant it would probably be closed down due to the 'excessive' radioactivity in it's walls. They are known to contain naturally occuring Uranium. <br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;...the NASA space nukes initiative represents the Bush administration's covert move to develop power systems for space-based weapons such as lasers on satellites. The military has often stated that their planned lasers in space will require enormous power projection capability and that nuclear reactors in orbit...&quot; <br>
<br>
The military abandoned it's nuclear space reactor (SP-100) in the 80's. This information of theirs is simply 20 years out of date. No doubt about it. The military certainly does have an interest in space. It would be wrong of the military not to investigate it's possibilities and I would have thought only a foreign power would support restricting such endeavours. <br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;NASA's nuclear rocket is a Trojan horse for the militarization of space.&quot;<br>
<br>
Technically it's assumed to be a reactor powered ion engine, SAFE, according to this pdf file by Michael Houts of the nuclear initiative team <br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings/outerplanets2001/pdf/4073.pdf">www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings...f/4073.pdf</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
not a nuclear rocket like NERVA which was an open Nuclear Thermal Reactor type engine suitable for an upper stage. NASA is a civilian agency and differentiated from the military. Ofcourse, the militarisation of space is eventually going to happen. The Air Force routinely flies aircraft at the edge of it. The prospect of others using space as a weapons platform is sufficient reason to warrant military access. <br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;In the end hundreds and hundreds of billions of dollars will be wasted on plans for the nuclearization and weaponization of space.&quot;<br>
<br>
How does he know this? Can the author provide a budget line item that has these figures? No. Because it's a flawed statement, an 'assumption'. Perhaps a quote on the market value of one moderate sized iron ore asteroid would fit in here rather nicely? Eros is estimated to be worth around 40 trillion dollars US in valuable resources including Platinum. It's true that Nasa has a zero profit policy but they will be opening the final frontier for others by showing the way. The wealth which could be ultimately generated is incalculable. Tourism, resources, energy production etc.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;Their plans now literally threaten the life of the entire planetary ecosystem.&quot;<br>
<br>
Doomsday scare tactics with no real science to back up the claim. Hundreds of high megaton nuclear bomb tests from the 50's and 60's released tons of Plutonium and highly enriched Uranium directly into the atmosphere and I would like to point out how the Earth did NOT become a wasteland as a result. The last launch of Plutonium by Nasa was Cassini back in 97 and the possibility of a launch failure was well planned for. The fuel was so well encased it would likely have been picked up and reused in a later mission if an unlikely accident had occured. The next planned Plutonium launch is for this Summer and it will carry 16 penny sized pellets of Plutonium for the twin Mars Rovers. Again, every precaution is being taken. It is ridiculous to hype up this miniscule risk when coal burning plants routinely churn out thousands of tons of Uranium and Thorium into the environment. Radioactive elements commonly found in coal beds and burned up with the coal before being pumped straight into our atmosphere. <br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;Ultimately NASA envisions mining colonies on the Moon, Mars, and asteroids that would be powered by nuclear reactors.&quot;<br>
<br>
This has never been NASA's goal. As a non-profit organisation they are largely restricted to exploration.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;All of the above missions would be launched from the Kennedy Space Center in Florida on rockets with a historic 10% failure rate. &quot; <br>
<br>
This is simply ignorant rhetoric. The shuttle's failure rate was certainly not 1 failure for every 10 launches. A failure does not automatically mean a big fireball on the pad or en-route either. Most failures are simply cancellations of the launch.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;In April, 1964 a U.S. military satellite with 2.1 pounds of plutonium-238 on-board fell back to Earth and burned up as it hit the atmosphere spreading the toxic plutonium globally as dust to be ingested by the people of the planet.&quot;<br>
<br>
The SNAP-9A RTG was an old 1960's design. The redesigned RTG's that launched after this have proven their safety with no release of radioactive elements despite two instances of catastrophic rocket failure. The newer designs have PROVED that they are safe even under the most extreme abuse. <br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;In order to fund these missions Bush and Congress will have to cut programs like social security, education, health care, child care, public transit and environmental protection. &quot;<br>
<br>
We should only spend money on social programs right. If any leader spouts this nonsense, you know it's close to election time. It's the tired old arguement of 'Why do we spend money on space when people are starving down here on earth?' Those against science and progress like to bring this question up repeatedly. The ancestors of these individuals were probably the same cave dwellers who spoke against messing with fire. &quot;It's a waste of time. It will never lead anywhere. Forget about it. There are more important things to do like picking berries from bushes and fleas from our scalps.&quot;<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;During the 1950s and 1960s NASA spent over $10 billion to build the nuclear rocket program which was cancelled in the end because of the fear that a launch accident would contaminate major portions of Florida and beyond.&quot;<br>
<br>
This is completely untrue. It was actually cancelled because Americans lost interest in a Mars Mission. Mr Gagnon is giving his fellow protestors an undeserved pat on the back here. Nuclear thermal rockets quietly faded away with our enthusiasm for space.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;NASA hasn't learned its lesson from its history involving space nuclear power,&quot; says Micho Kaku, &quot;and a hallmark of science is that you learn from previous mistakes. NASA doggedly pursues its fantasy of nuclear power in space.&quot;<br>
<br>
Fantasy of nuclear power in space? A large number of deep space probes and satellites already use nuclear RTG's. Our sun is a giant nuclear bomb. Even the Earth is now thought to be a giant reactor with a 5 mile wide Uranium core. Nuclear power is already firmly entrenched in space. The only mistake made was cancelling the reactor programs. Nuclear power is the only sensible option for serious space missions. That's why we are now finally returning to it big time. The biggest fantasy being doggedly pursued is the one Michio Kaku preaches. That solar power can do the job for us instead. This is a most impractical suggestion for missions to the outer reaches of the solar system where light is thousands of times dimmer.<br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;NASA, DoE, and the Pentagon are not asking the tax paying public if we want to suffer the risk and costs of nuclear power in space.&quot;<br>
<br>
I would welcome a public opinion poll asking this very question. There was one at Space.com a couple of years ago as I recall. It had the largest response in the history of the site. Well over 95% approval for a nuclear space initiative. Bruce Gagnon has always claimed to speak for the masses but I have yet to see any evidence in support of this assumption. Seventy five percent of people support space travel. Perhaps you should add a poll to your article. We have one just starting at our messageboards. 90% support so far but questioning purely space enthusiasts doesn't make for a general sample. <br>
<br>
Quote: &quot;NASA says that poses a 1-in-1,030 possibility of a radioactive accident near the launch site and, even in the worst-case scenario, the most exposed individuals would be subjected to less radiation than a single medical X-ray. &quot;<br>
&quot;NASA is lying,&quot; said Bruce Gagnon.<br>
<br>
No explanation or facts to back up his opinion... just simply, &quot;NASA is lying&quot;. <br>
<br>
Plutonium is often cited as the most toxic substance in the world. In truth, weight for weight, even caffeine is more toxic when ingested. The Alpha particles emitted from Plutonium decay can't even get through paper or skin. People have handled it without gloves and suffered no harm. <br>
<br>
Much of the radiation fear around today is a result of myths perpetuated by Hollywood. Recent hormesis research indicates that only extremely high dosages are damaging. Lower levels actually promote good health. Radiation is in fact necessary to stimulate DNA repair in the body. Some parts of the world such as India have natural background levels a hundred times higher and no harmful effects have been recorded.<br>
<br>
We used to use a linear threshold model for calculating radiation risk. This is now finally being put in the trash can. Just because 200 degrees heat will kill you does not mean that 20 degrees will kill 10% of you. It's gutter science for GNAWNPIS to perpetuate this archaic myth.<br>
<br>
Respectfully,<br>
Wayne Smith<br>
